# Zustand State Rules

## Why Zustand Here

Stores are created at module scope — outside React's component tree. State survives when containers remount (key-based reload, HMR, Suspense re-suspension). React Context would lose state on remount.

## Store Typing

Every store must have an explicit interface. The interface includes both state values and actions.

```typescript
// ✅ GOOD
interface ChatState {
  isOpen: boolean;
  toggleOpen: () => void;
  setOpen: (open: boolean) => void;
}

export const useChatStore = create<ChatState>((set) => ({
  isOpen: false,
  toggleOpen: () => set((s) => ({ isOpen: !s.isOpen })),
  setOpen: (open) => set({ isOpen: open }),
}));

// ❌ BAD — no interface, inline types
export const useChatStore = create((set) => ({
  isOpen: false,
  toggleOpen: () => set((s: any) => ({ isOpen: !s.isOpen })),
}));
```

## Naming

| Pattern | Convention |
|---------|-----------|
| Interface | `<Name>State` (e.g., `ChatState`) |
| Hook | `use<Name>Store` (e.g., `useChatStore`) |
| File | `<ContainerName>State.ts` (co-located) |

## Selectors — Always Use Them

```typescript
// ✅ GOOD — subscribes to specific slice
const isOpen = useChatStore((s) => s.isOpen);
const toggleOpen = useChatStore((s) => s.toggleOpen);

// ❌ BAD — subscribes to everything
const store = useChatStore();
```

## Co-location

- Container-specific stores: `src/containers/Chat/ChatState.ts`
- Shared stores (multi-container): `src/lib/stores/`
- Stores must never import from component files — data flows store → component

## Immutability

```typescript
// ✅ Spread nested objects
set((s) => ({ filters: { ...s.filters, status: "active" } }));

// ❌ Don't mutate in place
set((s) => { s.filters.status = "active"; return s; });
```
